The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport
		 Friday, June 18, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Kuala Lumpur: Afghanistan needed just 25 overs to upset Bahrain and score the war-torn countrys first victory in an international cricket tournament at the ACC Trophy in Malaysia. Chasing Bahrains 172, Afghan openers Karim Khan Sadiq and Nowraz Mangal slammed their more favoured rivals pace attack to notch up an opening partnership stand of 136 before Mangal was caught out for 60. Sadiq slammed 12 fours and three sixes on his way to his first century before being stumped for 109, leaving his team just four runs to get for the victory.				 																																	Bangalore: Throwing his weight behind the Badminton Association of Indias decision to allow players from south-east Asia to take part in three prize-money tournaments in India, Prakash Padukone said Indian shuttlers must face international competition at home and if they were scared, they should quit the game altogether. You have to be tough from a young age. You have to be prepared. If you are scared, then dont play, the badminton legend said. I personally feel that its good for the game in the long run. I am all for it. You get to play better players. You become tough. 				 																																	New Delhi: Top Seed Sunil Kumar Sipaeya crashed out of the ITF Satellite mens meet in the quarter finals on Thursday, losing to Vishal Uppal 6-7 (4-7), 6-4, 3-6 at the DLTA complex. The 22-year old lost his cool with a some line calls and then dropped serve to go down 3-5 in the third set. Uppal, then had no problems in serving out the set and match for a memorable victory.				 																																	OTHER RESULTS: Norikazu Sugiyama (Jpn, 2) bt Joshua Goodall (GBR, 7) 6-4, 6-4; Vinod Sridhar (Ind, 3) bt Mait Kunnap (Est, 6) 6-4, 6-2; Aqeel Khan (Pak) bt Ross Hutchins (GBR) 6-7 (4-7) 6-4, 6-4 .				 																																	London: Seeded third despite never having won a match at Wimbledon, Argentine Guillermo Coria has hastily appointed a new coach in a bid to hold his own at the grasscourt Grand Slam. Coria, who split with Fabian Blengino at Queens Club last week in the wake of his French Open final defeat, said on Thursday that he had agreed terms with a new mentor.				 																																	My new coach is my countryman Gabriel Makus, the world No. 3 said. We will begin to work together next Monday, when Wimbledon begins.				 																																	Coria said his agreement with Makus is until December.				 																																	Buenos Aires: Chelsea striker Hernan Crespo has been dropped by Argentina for next months Copa America in Peru. Crespo was omitted from a list of 12 foreign-based players for the July 6-25 tournament named by coach Marcelo Bielsa on Wednesday night.THE SQUADGoalkeeper: Pablo Cavallero (Celta Vigo). Defenders: Roberto Ayala (Valencia), Gabriel Heinze (Manchester United), Facundo Quiroga (Wolfsburg), Fabricio Coloccini (Villarreal), Javier Zanetti (Inter Milan), Diego Placente (Bayer Leverkusen), Juan Pablo Sorin (PSG). Midfielders: Kily Gonzalez (Inter Milan), Andres DAlessandro (Wolfsburg). Forwards: Javier Saviola (Barcelona), Cesar Delgado (Cruz Azul). Sport on Screen Soccer, Euro 2004: Bulgaria vs Denmark, live from 9.25 pm and Italy vs Sweden, live from 12.10 am (Saturday) on ESPN 
